Jim Crow activist and someone who was widely associated with accommodationism and wannabe whiteness. Historian Matthew Frye Jacobson attends to both threads, analyzing how industry norms, productions, scripts, roles, and audience expectations and responses were all framed by race against the backdrop of a changing America. In the spirit of better understanding Davis's life and career, Dancing Down the Barricades examines the complexities of his constraints, freedoms, and choices for what they reveal about Black history and American political culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEntertainerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aBlack music and dance.  aRat Pack.  abiography of Sammy Davis Jr.  acivil rights era.  ahistory of entertainment industry.  amid-twentieth century.  aminstrel tradition.  anetwork television.  apolitics of inclusion and exclusion.  arace and Hollywood.  avaudeville circuit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520391819?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520391819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520391819/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY